commentary: Sikandar Raza to NJ O'Brien, SIX runs oh dear, what's happened here? O'Brien stepped down the track and aimed a mighty swipe at the ball, but he got much more height than distance on the shot. Chamu Chibhabha ran across from long off, and seemed to get underneath it right in front of the sight screen ... but he spills it, and the ball bounces over the ropes. Worse, he seems to have hurt himself. He's down on the ground, and the physio has run out.

Worse, he seems to have hurt himself. He's down on the ground, and the physio has run out.

commentary: Masakadza to Wilson, no run this should have been a run out! Again Waller's fielding was the catalyst. Wilson stepped back and pulled very hard, but Waller sprinted to his right and dived down to stop the ball cleanly. His throw to Mutumbami was good, and Wilson, who had rushed down the track looking for a single, would have been well short. But Mutumbami fumbled the take and Wilson got home

commentary: Panyangara to KJ O'Brien, OUT what a catch! Raza is a bundle of energy down at long on. He'd had a go trying to stop the six that Wilson hit down the ground earlier in the over, and now he's pulled off a stunning catch. O'Brien chipped the ball, possibly looking to go straighter than he did, and Raza sprinted in from long-on. The ball was dying on him all the way, but he leapt forward at the very last moment to pluck it out of the air inches off the ground. That's a great effort, and he celebrates by flinging the ball high in to the clear blue sky

commentary: KJ O'Brien to Mutombodzi, OUT what a catch! This is a really special effort. Tino set himself to flick to leg but was too early into the shot. The ball looped in the air but seemed to be heading for empty space on the off side ... until Dockrell, who was at cover, charged round and timed his dive to snatch it mere inches from the turf. O'Brien certainly appreciates the effort, and celebrates the wicket with arms outstretched

commentary: Mooney to Sikandar Raza, 1 run Raza has demolished the stumps at the non-striker's end! I'm not sure there's a need for these sorts of singles. Raza nudged the ball towards point, where the fielder swooped very quickly. But Ervine called for the run, and Raza sprinted for the other end. Straight for the other end, and through the stumps as he leapt to make his ground.

Raza then pushes hard for what seemed an unlikely second, and gets home safely in the end!
